@node requirements
1. REQUIREMENTS

  Minimum system requirements for FPU in E
    "E" compiler :-)
    FPU.
@endnode

@node introduction
2. INTRODUCTION

  Floating  point  in  "E" consist of two modules.  First (main) is module,
called  "68881_single.m".  There are all functions of Your superb FPU chip,
ready to use/eat/something.  Second module "68881_test.m" is simple tester.
There  is  only  one  function, and it will help You decide if Your program
should  work,  like  crazy  (FPU  is  present  -  hardware is piece of good
silicon),  or  blame  user  (FPU  not present - hardware is piece of shit),
without any GURU.
@endnode

@node installation
3. INSTALLATION

  Simply copy all ".m" files somewhere. The best place is "emodules:fpu/",
but it is Your choice.
@endnode

@node usage
4. USAGE

  Ok.   You  have "E" FPU support modules installed.  I think, You know how
to  use  them,  so  I  don't  have  to  say  stuffs  like  writing  "MODULE
'fpu/68881_single'"  or  other  here.  There will be only SIMPLY SET OF ALL
INSTRUCTIONS:

"float"  -  is  an  floating  point number ("E" can handle single precision
floating  point numbers.  Just write 3.14 or 1.0, or 0.001 - there are used
by  compiler  as  floating point numbers.  See chapter of "E" manual called
"floating  point  support".   FPU  in  E  is  compatible  with "E" floating
numbers,  so  You  can  use  i.e  "RealF()",  "RealVal()" functions for FPU
floating numbers)

         fabs(float)           = Absolute Value of "float"
         facos(float)          = Arc Cosine of "float"
         fadd(float1,float2)   = "float1" + "float2"
         fasin(float)          = Arc Sine of "float"
         fatan(float)          = Arc Tangent of "float"
         fcmp(float1,float2)   = Results are integer! -1 if float1<float2
                                                        0 if float1=float2
                                                        1 if float1>float2
 
         fcos(float)           = Cosine of "float"
         fcosh(float)          = Hyperbolic Cosine of "float"
         fdiv(float1,float2)   = "float1" / "float2"
         fetox(float)          = e^"float"
         fetoxm1(float)        = e^"float"-1
         fgetexp(float)        = Exponent of "float"
         fgetman(float)        = Mantissa of "float"
         fint(float)           = Integer part of "float" - result is FLOAT
         fintrz(float)         = Round-to-Zero integer part of "float"
                                                   (See fint(float) !)
         flog10(float)         = Log[10] of "float"
         flog2(float)          = Log[2] of "float"
         flogn(float)          = Log[e] of "float"
         flognp1(float)        = Log[e] of ("float"+1)
         fmod(float1,float2)   = "float1" MOD "float2"
         fmul(float1,float2)   = "float1" * "float2"
         fneg(float)           = -"float"
         frem(float1,float2)   = IEEE Remainder of "float1" and "float2"
         fscale(float1,float2) = "float2" * Int(2^"float1")
         fsin(float)           = Sine of "float"
         fsinh(float)          = Hyperbolic Sine of "float"
         fsqrt(float)          = Square Root of "float"
         fsub(float1,float2)   = "float1" - "float2"
         ftan(float)           = Tangent of "float"
         ftanh(float)          = Hyperbolic Tangent of "float"
         ftentox(float)        = 10 ^ "float"
         ftoreal(integer)      = Converts integer to "float"
         ftointeger(float)     = Converts float to integer
         ftwotox(float)        =  2 ^ "float2

And in "68881_test.m" module:
         ftestiffpu()          = result is TRUE  - FPU is present
                                            FALSE - There is NO FPU

Everything clear ? See @{"examples" link examples}, and @{"benchmarks" link benchmarks}.
@endnode          
 
